******
[4] South Dakota (McPherson County): commercial turkeys
Date: Mon 26 Sep 2022
Source: WattPoultry.com [abridged, edited]
https://www.wattagnet.com/articles/45857-avian-flu-strikes-in-south-dakota-alberta-saskatchewan


The North American outbreak of highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) continues as new cases have emerged in South Dakota, Alberta, and Saskatchewan.

The presence of HPAI was confirmed in a commercial turkey flock in McPherson County, South Dakota, on 22 Sep [2022], reported the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service (APHIS). There were 15 000 turkeys in that flock.

The McPherson County case was confirmed 2 days after APHIS reported the presence of the virus in 2 other South Dakota turkey flocks, both of which were in Clark County.

This is McPherson County's 5th case of HPAI in commercial poultry, all of which involved turkeys. As a whole, South Dakota has had 39 cases of HPAI in commercial poultry.

[Byline: Roy Graber]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mahmoud Orabi

[ProMED map of South Dakota, United States: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8705832,243]

[It is autumn migration of birds, from the north back to the south. Be alert for any signs of illness in your flocks.

Although the articles included in this report do not acknowledge the avian flu virus as HPAI H5N1, it is the current strain in circulation.

Biosecurity is the utmost of importance. Autumn migration southward is occurring, and just as the spring migration brought this disease in the spring, it is continuing to spread on the trip south for the migratory birds. Be sure your biosecurity is functioning at a very high level. - Mod.TG]
